\]

4. From \( B_3 = 16 \):
\[ B_4 = 
\begin{cases} 
3 \cdot 16 - 1 = 47 & \text{with probability } \frac{1}{2} \\
16 + 1 = 17 & \text{with probability } \frac{1}{2}
\end{cases}
\]

Expected \( B_4 \) given \( B_3 \):
\[ E(B_4 | B_3 = 122) = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 365 + \frac{1}{2} \cdot 123 = \frac{365 + 123}{2} = 244 \]
\[ E(B_4 | B_3 = 42) = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 125 + \frac{1}{2} \cdot 43 = \frac{125 + 43}{2} = 84 \]
\[ E(B_4 | B_3 = 44) = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 131 + \frac{1}{2} \cdot 45 = \frac{131 + 45}{2} = 88 \]
\[ E(B_4 | B_3 = 16) = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 47 + \frac{1}{2} \cdot 17 = \frac{47 + 17}{2} = 32 \]

Using the law of total expectation again:
\[ E(B_4) = \frac{1}{4} \cdot 244 + \frac{1}{4} \cdot 84 + \frac{1}{4} \cdot 88 + \frac{1}{4} \cdot 32 = \frac{244 + 84 + 88 + 32}{4} = \frac{448}{4} = 112 \]

